recallreText: The ant studied in the passage was unique in that it evolved a very powerful jaw. That jaw functioned by closing very quickly using the energy stored within the jaw muscles, closing at incredibly fast speeds. That jaw was useful in that it was very strong and able to pierce the shells of its pray and consume the meat inside easily, and it used its jaw mechanisms to perform a couple types of unique jumps, a type of escape jump, which evolved essentially by accident, and a type of defense jump. The escape jump has the ant slamming its face on the ground, which propels the ant to a point where it may better attack the intruder in its nest and/or the ant's pray. The defense jump has the ant slamming its face against its enemy, which both forces the enemy out of the ants nest, and propels the ant also out of the nest, or in the opposite direction of the enemy. The ant's jaw mechanics are studied by four distinct researchers. The field researchers who study the ants liken trying to capture the ants as trying to catch hot popcorn, because they frantically jump around when encountering an intruder, and because there is a bad sting when the ant bites the intruder.
recall3DaysreText: In The Jaws That Jump, the passage talked about a specific species of ant, the biology behind its jaw mechanisms, and how it uses those jaw mechanisms to perform a few special kinds of jumps. The jaws functioned by storing large amounts of energy within the jaw muscles that allowed the jaw to close at extremely fast speeds. Researchers who study this species of ant recalled that trying to catch this ant was like trying to catch popping pop corn, because when they encountered an intruder or researcher, they would be jumping all around, impossible to catch. Researchers also mentioned that because of their powerful jaw, getting bit by one of the ants was particularly painful. The passage mentioned that their jaw and bite was so powerful, it was able to crack the exoskeletons of their pray so that they were easily able to access the meat inside. There are two types of jumps that the passage mentioned: a defense jump and an escape jump. The defense jump worked with the ant slamming its face and jaw against the ground to launch it into the air. This is done so that the ant could reach a better vantage point to attack its enemy. The second type of jump, the escape jump, worked with the ant slamming its face/jaw against its attacker. This is done so that the ant can propel the intruder out of the ant's nest, and propel the ant in the opposite direction, or also out of the nest, so that it may escape the intruder. The passage mentioned that the escape jump may have evolved by accident.

recallreText:
Trap-jaw ants have very powerful jaws and several different types of jumps that use the jaws.
Their jaws are open very wide (180 degrees or more) until something brushes the trigger hairs inside the mandible, and the jaws spring shut.
The jaws decelerate as they shut so that the ant doesn't hurt itself.
The energy is stored in the muscles of the mandible, just like firing an arrow with a bow.
The ants have an escape jump, which bounces them in all kinds of directions very quickly. This jump was discovered accidentally by
They also have a bouncer-defense jump, which propels the ant (and potentially the attacker, if it's small enough) out of the nest in different directions.
recall3DaysreText: The trap-jaw ants have very powerful (due to muscles) jaws that can open 180 degrees or more. They spring shut when something brushes against a trigger hair on the inside of the mandible, but the jaws decelerate as they get closer together so that the jaw snapping shut doesn't hurt the ant. They also have a couple of different jumps they can do should there be a predator or attacker near. One of them is the bouncer-defense jump, in which the ants can launch themselves in one direction out of the nest just a little bit off the ground, and they can potentially launch the attacker in another direction if the attacker is small enough. They also have the escape jump, which is when the ant launches itself into the air very high in a random direction, like popcorn. It was created as a jump by accident, when one ant banged its head against the ground and it ended up being beneficial.

recallreText: Bacteria provide a great example of how evolution takes place. recall3DaysreText: Molecular evolution provides a short way to show how evolution works. During DNA replication, these genes would cause a mutation in the DNA, which can lead to the development of abilities such as eating citrate.

There were two distinct attacks that the researchers were able to note that the ants make use of. One is the escape jump, which allows the ant to jump very high in a random direction away from an intruder, in order to reposition themselves for a potential counter attack. The other is the bounce-defense jump, which involves the ant using propulsion from their jaw to launch an intruder away from their nest (if the intruder is small enough), while also launching back the attacker. The ants have been compared to popping popcorn, as they jump in a frenzy whenever they are approached by an invader to their home.

The force of the ant's powerful jaw is able to break through the shells of most of their prey, and it is able to prevent harm on the ant itself by decelerating slightly before coming to a complete stop. Researchers described two specific uses that the ant have for their propulsion abilities. In one case, ants are able to propel themselves up in a random direction when approached by a threat, which allows the ant to assess the situation, and potentially land in a spot better suited for counter attacking. In the other case, the ant is able to apply significant force on its opponent, and if it is small enough, the opponent will be launched out of the nest. The recoil of this attack also pushes back the ant slightly.

recallreText:
Trap-jaw ants have three anatomical features that some scientists recently made a study of. 

The first is their trap-jaws, which they use for self-defense as well as preying on smaller insects.  Their strong but slow jaw muscles store energy like an archer in a bowthey open as much as 140 degrees, and then snap shut at 135 miles per hour.

The second is their "bouncer-defense", whereby they expel attackers out of their nest by slamming into them.  This also sends the ant flying! 

The third is their escape-jump, which they use when another being intrudes on their nest.  They jump high into the air, allowing them to live another day, or even setting up another attack on the intruder.  

Though they are both aerial techniques, the bouncer defense and the escape jump most likely evolved separately.

Some miscellanea: they nest in leafy debris rather than mounds or logs.
recall3DaysreText:
The passage was about a particular kind of ant (trap-jaw ants) who have three rather unique physiological defense mechanisms. 

First, they have the ability to store kinetic energy in their jaw muscles to an extraordinary degree---they can open their jaws up to 150 degrees and snap them shut at up to 135 miles per hour.  They use this for predation, and also as a defense mechanismwhen other animals intrude on their hives, which they construct in piles of loose leaves on the floor of the region where they live, they go after them.

They also have the capability to perform an escape jump, which helps them escape from predators.  When they're defending their hive, this gives them the incidental ability to move to new positions whence to bite their attackers.

Finally, they do what the article called a "bouncer defense"they slam into intruders and send both them and the ant flying.  This is believed to have evolved separately from the escape jump, which is interesting, because their physiological mechanisms are related.

recallreText: The researchers left strains of bacteria in 12 flasks for over 2 decades to examine the stripped-down essentials of evolution, without human interaction or the presence of other species.  While the bacteria in the flasks seemed to develop almost identically for a certain number of generations, they found that there were larger and smaller colonies of bacteria - the size difference was due in part to random mutations, which led to certain colonies metabolizing glucose more efficiently than others.  The smaller colonies were able to survive off of the byproducts of the larger colonies.  The researchers also found that after 31000 generations, a new strain of bacteria formed, with an ability to consume citrate, which clearly differentiates it from e. coli, which cannot consume citrate.
recall3DaysreText: Researchers allowed e. coli bacteria to multiply for multiple decades in order to watch evolution stripped down to the essentials.  One of the key things that they noticed was that after 35000 generations, one of the beaker's populations mutated into a new kind of bacteria differentiated from e. coli by the fact that it could consume citrate, something which e. coli cannot do.  This mutation was random, as there was no human intervention or other species passing through that could cause this change.  Ultimately these random mutations caused differences in the populations like the maximum size of the bacteria.

recallreText: The jaw-trap ant has powerful mandibles due to its muscles that store up energy. It doesn't hurt itself because the mandible decelerates once it approaches to closing. It's in South America. It has two types of jumps, the defensive bounce and the escape jump. The escape jump is used to evade a predator (like a lizard's tongue) by slamming its mandibles against the ground, making it unpredictable. It was likely evolved on accident and the passage had the best way to phrase it "the only time where banging ur head against the ground was a good thing" (something like that). It also gives the ant another chance for a counterattack by moving to a new location. Meanwhile, the bounce jump propels the ant and even the imposter of the nest (if light enough) in opposite directions. Several ants can team up in what I'm imagining is a real-life pinball machine to get the intruder out. The bounce jump was likely discovered through many failed attempts in attacking the intruder. The trap-jaw ant has the fastest bite, unparalleled in other animals, going over 400mph(?). It can also use the mandibles to get through hard-shelled prey.
recall3DaysreText: The jaw-trap ant have evolved an interesting way to use their mandibles. They have the fastest biting speed in the animal world. They have two different jumps, the defend bounce jump and the escape jump. The escape jump was done by banging its head against the ground (the only good thing that came around from banging head against floor, as the passage says) and it lets the ant make a fast unexpected move to avoid the sticky tongue of a lizard and gives it the opportunity to regroup for another attack. The defense bounce jump can propel the ant and the intruder (if light enough) in opposite directions and likely evolved from many fails at attacking an intruder. The ant lives in South America? Evolution is weird.
